I finally found time to look for the meta. Relatively straightforward, as no knowledge of pop culture or sports was required.

CRAIG BIRKER subscriber 5pts 
On shore! Fun meta! (Heidi)

Cynthia Weatherman subscriber 5pts 
The mgwcc is one cool construction.
Diana Breithaupt user 5pts 
Still at sea. My latest excuse is that I just did the grid this morning, which is a true story. I got the first step. But then I set it aside to do the MGWCC because I wanted to be high on leaderboard. After an hour or more, I realized that was not going to happen, so I checked the leaderboard to see if it was difficult or if I was just stupid. 

There were only 5 people on the leaderboard and you know who was No. 2? Our very own Muggle, Al Sisti. If you don't do the MGWCC, you don't know how difficult that is to accomplish on a Week 3. There he is - sitting pretty at No. 2. I am proud, as a fellow Muggle. 

Still at sea on both puzzles, though. 
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Diana Breithaupt I am highly confident that you will solve both metas. I am also not surprised that Al is at the top of the leaderboard. I still want a video of him solving one of these although it may take a high speed camera. I remain in awe. Al Sisti user 5pts 
@ Robert Stevens @ Diana Breithaupt You guys are way too kind. Sometimes you just fall into the right path the first time. Still nowhere near in the same league as a lot of the muggles here -- including Diana and Cindy, who are both perfect this year, and Meg, whose current streak is an amazing 75 straight!
Cynthia Weatherman subscriber 5pts 
Today completes my 52 week mgwcc streak.
Now. I am going for a perfect 2018 record - wsj, mgwcc, mmmm and fireball. So far so good but there is a lot of year left. 
And you are right Al. Sometimes you just see it.
JOHN BENNETT subscriber 5pts 
Alright - the nice weather in Montana had me on the golf course yesterday, rather than puzzling.

Onshore.

Very nice puzzle!
John Wheeler user 5pts 
Well that was clever. Thanks Marie, uh--Mike.
Ashore
Mary Flaminio user 5pts 
Onshore? Always doubt my answers.

Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Mary Flaminio I have you as being on shore six weeks and not stuck on the ship. You should not doubt yourself
Bunny Zukowski user 5pts 
Safely onshore. Very cute.

now on to the MWCC
Glyn Short user 5pts 
I think I've solved it, but I am not sure I'm on shore: I need to be assured...
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Glyn Short If you are not sure, dig deeper. This is a no doubter
James Cornell subscriber 5pts 
Ashore, but hoping it's the right beach. Puzzle seemed a bit too easy this week, but my answer hits all the marks and sometimes it just comes to you immediately. Usually not, though. Have a great weekend everyone!

Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ James Cornell this is one of those "no doubter" solutions. 
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
Our quick Friday noon report. We have had a lot of muggles jumping ship and 46 are currently on the warm shore with their mai tais from the tiki bar.

A bunch of others are digging in the rabbit holes and are surely headed towards the shore. We are sure they will be joining us. M Lembo user 5pts 
The correct answer is so much better than my imagined ones, which aren't that bad - they're just drawn that way? After a short swing by to say 'bye' to Isaac, I am ashore.

Have a great weekend everyone.
Stu Katz user 5pts 
Unless it's classified information, could someone please enlighten me as to whether Marie Kelly is a real female person? I ask because I have seen comments from time to time (including this week) alluding to a different gender. Thanks. 

Lisa Young user 5pts 
@ Stu Katz "Marie Kelly" is an anagram of "Really Mike", meaning Mike Shenk.
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Stu Katz https://www.crosswordtournament.com/2016/constructors.htm Stu Katz user 5pts 
@ Robert Stevens @ Stu Katz This reply is to both Lisa and Robert.

First, thanks for the quick turnaround, Lisa. I was hoping it was either the real name or a pseudonym of one of the great female puzzlers, of which (as we know) there are plenty (topped by the "E" in HEX). 


Second, thanks for the link Robert. 


By the way, immediately after posting my query, I Googled "Marie Kelly puzzle" and saw the answer to my question (of course). The problem I then encountered was that I couldn't delete my post or edit it despite three separate efforts.even though it was within 5 minutes of my post. Rather than trying to master the art of commenting , I will just try to be more judicious when I comment after this. 

Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Stu Katz @ Robert Stevens Do not worry about posting and then regretting it. We all have done it. No harm, no foul Stu Katz user 5pts 
@ Robert Stevens @ Stu Katz Thanks for your words of comfort, Robert. Whether or not an official position, you are doubtless one of the de facto chaplains of our ship.
PETER LEE subscriber 5pts 
Feeling a bit exasperated, as everyone sauntered to shore this week, while I feel like I have 95% for it and a pretty solid idea as to the answer but there's one piece missing for me that I would rather nail down to ensure I'm not actually deep in the wrong rabbit hole. So count me as at sea at this point but with land in sight.
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ PETER LEE Will do but I am sure you are on the right track. Keep digging in that rabbit hole and listen for the call of the wild Barbara Hays subscriber 5pts 
Clever construction!

Richard L Johnson subscriber 5pts 
(Cynthia) Solved and on shore.

Mary Ellen Price user 5pts 
My husband and I traveled to our "summer" cottage in Michigan yesterday. I'm looking out the window at a frozen lake this morning. Very pretty, but cold. I have a lot of cleaning and unpacking to do, so I'm glad to be ashore, albeit a frozen one. Good luck, fellow muggles. 
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Mary Ellen Price How much ice is on the lake?
Mary Ellen Price user 5pts 
@ Robert Stevens @ Mary Ellen Price A neighbor told us the ice is about a foot deep?! I haven't personally checked that out yet, and I won't venture to walk on it, but i t looks frozen as far as I can see. The lake is about 4 miles wide and 10 miles long. There's at least 12 inches of snow on the ground, and some of the drifts are much deeper. We had to have someone plow out our lane so we could get in here. My husband's first priority is to de-winterize the hot tub. Mine was to solve the meta. :) 
Cynthia Weatherman subscriber 5pts 
I am still mugless but now I have my "Fireball Crosswords" ball cap. Nice cap but not my style, LOL! I did put it on yesterday while still dressed from the office to surprise my husband when he came in. He was delayed and by the time he got home, I had forgotten that I was wearing it. The look on his face was priceless. I gave him the cap for putting up with my meta obsession.
Diana Breithaupt user 5pts 
@ Cynthia Weatherman 

Does your cap look like this
Cynthia Weatherman subscriber 5pts 
No photo
THOMAS BURNAKIS subscriber 5pts 
OMG I GOT it, after three weeks of sniffing around rabbit holes and pulling out my hair (neat trick since I am follicularly challenged to start) this one came so easy I am almost ashamed. Please note I said almost!

This is the first time I even knew the puzzle was available on Thursday which is comforting because I was always AMAZED that so many folks could have the answer seemingly instantaneously. The only post-crosswordal remorse I have is that it is now over way too soon and I'll have to wait until Friday (well obviously Thursday) to do it again. Of course there is always the nagging feeling that I have not done it right - must be Episcopal guilt?

Thanks Marie for another clever puzzle. There is an association and comment I would love to make, but I am sure it would be a spoiler so I will wait until Sunday night or Monday to post it.
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ THOMAS BURNAKIS Thomas. Now you will be looking at your computer around 4:15 Eastern time every Thursday and printing it out. What will amaze you is how fast Al and some of the others solve it week in and week out. 

I suspect that there will be a bunch of comments on Monday
Cynthia Weatherman subscriber 5pts 
@ THOMAS BURNAKIS Subscribe to MGWCC and then you will have entertainment/angst from noon Friday forward.
Howard Green subscriber 5pts 
On shore with a bit of help from my consortium. Enjoyed it a lot, Mr. Kelly.
Frank Ho user 5pts 
I have been keeping Isaac company for such a long time. Wait , what is this? I am on shore!
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Frank Ho hopefully the start of a long run on shore patrol
Chris Kochmanski subscriber 5pts 
Ashore! 
This one came pretty fast. We had about an hour and a half before having to leave for the airport to pick up the kids. I thought, "Well, I'll get started." Grid plus meta in about 50 minutes. That's close to my fastest, in about six or eight months of doing these.
Nino Mosca 5pts 
A few weeks ago, I thought I saw LOVE forming squares around the letters of ARGO, but I knew it wasn't elegant enough to be the true solution, so I did not submit it. (It turned out that what I was seeing was the four letters of the word "enVELOpe" forming squares around the word ARGO.)

Once again, I think I am almost there, but not quite...

It's only Thursday...
JOSEPH MICHAEL subscriber 5pts 
@ Nino Mosca Funny, I got "Argo" that week as the meta without once noticing the "envelope" theme at all. it was the only movie title that fit all the references to Greek mythology in the grid itself. BTW, I would really like to see an actual movie made from Zelazny's Lord of Light , a magnificent novel (the book the movie-makers in Argo supposedly were turning into a movie).
David Oakes user 5pts 
Hardly ever get Marie's metas!

But this one fell into place almost at first glance -wading ashore with much celebration, assuming of course the answer was correct!

More certain than the Hunt for Red October of course... 
Kas DeCarvalho user 5pts 
...is anyone else seeing the article, "How the Caddyshack Revolution Upended Hollywood" under the comments? (Complete with Bill Murray and gopher photo...) It's just making me chuckle in the context of all the "rabbit hole" comments...the Meta frequently makes me feel decidedly Murray-ish...in hindsight, we should have gone with a gopher theme, instead of rabbits. Oh, and I haven't started the grid yet, just a little post-printing lurking for psychic support...
Robert Stevens subscriber 5pts 
@ Kas DeCarvalho Kas - I saw that and had the same chuckle. Good luck on the grid. It is between a 1 and 2 on your scale
JOHN WEBBER subscriber 5pts 
18 minutes to complete the grid, thanks to the delay from 8A, which gets my personal prize for best clue of the week. Tomorrow afternoon, consideration of the meta.

Bill Schapiro subscriber 5pts 
@ JOHN WEBBER I would have thought your favorite clue was not 8A, but rather near 8A.
Beth Albers user 5pts 
On the beach! Enjoyed it!
Stephen McNeil subscriber 5pts 
On shore. Now on to keep my (maybe first ever) three week streak alive for MGWCC.
